# Terminology
[[Unsorted/Appendix#Plant morphology fruits\|Appendix#Plant morphology fruits]]


# What is a fruit?
- Plant organs that contain seeds
- Produced by [[angiosperms\|angiosperms]] only
- Includes edible fruits and the seeds of wild oats
- After pollination, ovules develop into seeds, and the ovary wall forms the pericarp (fruit tissue)
- The fruit represents the genetics of the plant which produced the fruit
	- NOT the genetics of the seed inside the fruit
## Functions
- Protects the seed embryo
- Can also help with dispersing the seeds
- Many seeds need to go through the guts of an animal
	- We can artificially replicate some of these things

## Types
- Simple fruits
	- A single fertilized ovary from a single flower
	- Examples
		- Single Berries (IE Tomatoes)
		- Drupes
			- Plums, peaches. cherries, olives
		- False berries
			- Accessory fruits: banana, cranberry, etc
		- Pome
			- Accessory fruits: Apple, pear, rosehip
- Aggregate fruits
	- Multiple fertilized seeds produced by a single flower
		- Many achenes with a single seed each
	- IE
		- Strawberries
- Composite fruits
	- "Multiple fruits"
	- Many ovaries that combine into one fruit
- Legumes
	- Composed of one carpel that splits into 2
	- 
- Capsules
- Nuts
- Grains

## Parthenocarpy
- The development of fruit without fertilization
	- Very highly-sought trait
	- Occurs in
		- Pineapples, bananas, grapes, oranges, grapes, etc
	- Parthenocarpy can be forced by applying dead or altered pollen
		- Can also be forced by injecting synthetic growth substances
	- Comes from triploid by breeding diploid plants with tetraploid plants
		- Has to be done every generation

## Fruit classification
- Fleshy
	- Wet and sweet
	- IE Apples, oranges, etc
- Dry
	- Peas, corn, maple seeds
